posts.raw_content:
If we lived in a sane/just society, you'd think that the word Bolshevik slapped onto somebody would be a lot more inflammatory and insulting than Nazi.

Because the Bolsheviks were way worse than the Nazis, having committed far more death and destruction by comparison. The former group had a much bigger body count. Stalin alone killed like at least four times as many people as Hitler did.

You know, I think there's been some heavy misrepresentation in terms of how 20th century dictators have been depicted in media and how we've been taught about them. You'd be led into believing that Hitler was the worst of them, and that he's basically *synonymous* with human evil.

But I can't help but think that there's something off about that. Other dictators of the same time period had bigger scopes of war crimes. Like I said, Stalin killed way more people, and so did Mao. And so by all accounts, Stalin should be significantly more infamous than Hitler, *but he's not.*

In fact, the same people who demonize the hell out of Hitler and the Nazis (the left) and constantly compare us to them don't seem to care enough to do the same about Stalin and the Bolsheviks. And not just that, but they even seem to have positive opinions of the Bolsheviks!

It makes me think about how bad of a decision it was to team up with Russia during World War 2. We should've considered them an enemy like we did with Germany.
